            <notesStmt>
                <note type="summary">
                    
                        
                            
                            <p>Letter from William Sheehan (b.1877), clerk of the Fermoy Urban District, to Ivor Guest, the Lord Wimborne, (1873-1939), lord lieutenant of Ireland. The letter concerns a malicious injury  claim made by Sarah J. Rowe (b.1868) due to the death of her husband William N. Rowe (1867-1916), RIC constable who was shot in an attempt to arrest members of the Kent family in connection with Sinn Fein activity in County Cork. Thomas Kent (1865-1916) was later executed for the murder of Constable Rowe. The letter also has a copy of a resolution made regarding the case, calling on the authorities to pay Mrs Rowe some form of compensation. It goes on to state that the application for the fund to be levied off the rate payers should be withdrawn, so not to disturb the peace.</p>
                            
                        
                            
                        
                            
                            <p> Ivor Churchill Guest, 1st Viscount Wimborne was appointed the Lord Lieutenant of Ireland in 1915. Guest worked closely alongside Sir Matthew Nathan (1862-1939) in the administration of Ireland. Following the suppression of the Rising, Guest, under pressure, was forced to resign as Lord Lieutenant. A later inquiry into the Rising exonerated Guest and held Augustine Birrell (1850-1933) chiefly responsible for the events that occurred. Guest would continue to serve as Lord Lieutenant until 1918.</p>
                            
                        
                    
                </note>
